Triumph of the right-wing populists in Austria, total they come to 29 percent
A noticeable weakening of both parties of the large coalition so far and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties brought, after the first preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections of Sunday in Austria.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly severe losses, where the position of former chairman Wilhelm Molterer is seriously on the decline.
In contrast, the head of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Carinthian state captain Jörg Haider, is preparing for a triumphant return to federal politics.
According to the results so far, the Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest in the country with 29.8 percent of the votes, but compared to the last elections in 2006, it loses 5.5 percent of the votes.
Even worse, the ÖVP lost almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in Austrian post-war history, and especially with the People’s Party, which had called for the early elections, this is a truly catastrophic result.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP had left the coalition, the People's Party had a clear lead over the SPÖ.
But voters have probably punished the party for failing the government.
Already in the first reactions to the results, there were speculations about a possible resignation of the party chairman and former vice chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers think this could be the case as early as Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party's board.
Such a development would probably pave the way to the most likely way out of the electoral debacle, i.e. to a renewal of the large coalition of SPÖ and ÖVP.
Given the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ) received provisionally 18%, the BZÖ 11% of the vote - the Social Democrats expressed at the same time their fear that the year 1999 could repeat itself, when the People's Party had agreements with the populists (at the time the FPÖ was still united), which had split from the European Union in 2005.
This development is obviously Jörg Haider, who has already declared that he is ready to cooperate with each party and assumes a return to Vienna in Austrian federal politics.
The Green Party also entered the parliament, but suffered slight losses and slipped from third to fifth place among the Austrian political parties.
No other party has probably mastered the four-percent hurdle and therefore did not enter Parliament.
