Turkey expands diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey sought to join the European Union, the European powers were interested in penetrating deep into the hinterland of Turkey.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps inside Asia, stands one of the finest relics of this failed imperial endeavor.
The Hydarpasha station was designed by the two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in the Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that’s what the guides tell you.
The building sits at the end of the platforms with a tower at each corner of the front and looks like any provincial German Town Hall.
The rock is dirty.
The entire building is decaying.
But once you’re inside the domed ticket counter, there’s no doubt about the grandeur of the project, whose westernmost access was this.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Bagdad Society.
Germany, which was a delay in the imperialist game, had to implement its ambitions to dominate the Middle East, by means of a train connection to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany’s imperialist plans were paralyzed during the First World War.
His rails were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arabs.
The relative isolation from its surrounding region, generated by the insurmountable boundaries of the Cold War, has disappeared.
British forces moved out of Egypt, pushing the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria
And there was also bad news for the Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, a train of ammunition flew into the air, destroying the artful roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly decayed, largely bypassed by history.
Nowadays, however, this railway line, at least symbolically, serves as a gateway to Anatolia and everything east of it, to highlight the expansion of the diplomatic horizon of Turkey.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the ACP, has introduced a voluntarily new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from neighbouring regions, generated by the Cold War borders, has disappeared.
There is now a policy of rapprochement.
Remarkably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian splitter groups Hamas and Fatah, with Iran and Iraq and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to assess the key data of this new foreign policy, I boarded the night train to the Turkish capital Ankara to visit one of the leading ACP foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, about ten and a half hours later, after a bumpy ride on tracks that produced the step of the old world in the well-known documentary "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital, which is regarded as a new city, for the new secular state project, to turn its back on the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, known for its Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in Turkish unity.
This has sparked a lot of suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi took me to the AKP headquarters, a specially crafted, ultra-modern stone and steel structure, in an evolving suburb, surrounded by semi-finished shopping malls and pubs where middle managers in suits, both men and women, met to complete the first shops of the day.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a center-right politician of almost any other political party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he even packed a blackberry.
“The objective of the Party’s foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey with its immediate neighbours.
The Cold War was an exceptional event,” he tells me.
Turkey had been cut off from its hinterland.
Nowadays, it has to look east and west at the same time.
There would not be either one or the other.
She would have to do both.
“But surely Turkey could at some point,” I asked, “be forced to decide?”
"Turkey," he said, "would not have to face this decision."
He then highlighted a point that almost everyone I spoke to here routinely said: Turkey's relations, not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, are just as beneficial for Europe and the United States as they are for Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be that Europe as a whole can, in a transfigured sense, travel eastwards on the same railroad tracks to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha’s station, after another largely sleepless night, I thought of these two German lords Mr. Ritter and Mr. Conu, who had watched this building 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to learn that Europe’s ambitions in the Middle East could now be in the hands of Turkey, to a large extent.
And as I waited at the dock for the ferry to take me back over the Bosphorus, I remembered that Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe" in those days.
At the time, at least, there did not seem to be much doubt as to which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
In memory of Vernon Handley and William Woodruff.
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's musical director since 1962, Vernon "Death" Handley was responsible for the Guildford Philharmonic and Choir.
As part of his music program for the city, he founded his great youth choir, Proteus, the following year.
It was intended for teenagers up to 21 years old, but when the choir sang for the last time in 1979 some of us were already at the end of 20 - we simply refused to leave the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological shape changer) stood for the willingness and ability of the choir to tackle any piece of music presented to him, whether it was a madrigal or from the Messiah, whether a capella or with full orchestra.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often astonishing, always exciting and lasted only thanks to the inspiration of that man and his enthusiasm for the music that never gave up for years.
How often did death stop us to “let the music speak for itself.”
He used to say, "The composer knows what he wants."
It's all in the music.
Sing it!"
His manner of conducting was absolutely clear and precise, never masterful but never overwhelming.
Whatever the musical level was, he always demanded an even higher level.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor should have been beaten to become a knight, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the last two decades, from 1962 to 1982, during which he directed the Guildford Philharmonic.
For the past 40 years or so, I’ve written reviews for over a hundred of his concerts and I can honestly say that I’ve never been disappointed by a single person—often I’ve been inspired by them.
Tod Handley was that rare combination of size and personal humility.
He hated conductors who, according to him, simply "go home with one or two well-known showhorses in the world."
So many of us will miss him.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
In your obituary for William Woodruff (September 25), you write that "he resumed teaching economic history at Oxford in 1946 and received a Houblon-Norman research scholarship in 1950 ... while studying at the same time for a BSc, an MA and a PhD degree.
This is a conclusion from an author’s remark in Woodruff’s book “Beyond Nab End,” but it’s not true.
From 1946 to 1953 he was a lecturer in economic history at the University of Nottingham and during this time he wrote a doctoral thesis on the British rubber industry under the supervision of Professor J.D. Chambers, which was later published in 1958 as "The British Rubber Industry".
He was in the United States in 1950-1951 on a Houblon-Norman scholarship, and spent the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, Harvard, and New York.
In 1953, he left Nottingham permanently and went to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff wanted to cover up this part of his career.
