‘Auto-bee’ that avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of accident prevention technologies, this time Nissan was inspired by nature, more precisely, by bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot whose flight stems from the swarming behavior of bees and prevents accidents.
This robot is a Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C and represents the first step in accident prevention technologies.
The engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Technical Development Center have developed this small robot in cooperation with the Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the renowned University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, head of technology PR and R&D brand management, the BR23C represents an extension of the four-layer Nissan safety shield.
This robot is meant to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid the collisions.
During the flight, each bee builds its own oval-shaped airspace, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important thing is the bee’s faceted eyes, which can see at an angle of 300 degrees in all directions, which allows her to fly undisturbed in her personal airspace without interruption.
In order to replicate the all-round perspective, the technicians developed the so-called Laser Range Finder (LRF).
It notices obstacles up to two meters apart in front of the BR23C and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an onboard microprocessor, which is immediately translated into a collision avoidance signal.
At the moment when obstacle is noticed, the little robot will mimic the bee flight and immediately change direction by rotating its wheels by 90o or even greater angle to avoid collision.
The biggest difference to any other system is that this evasion manoeuvre takes place absolutely instinctively.
If it weren’t, the robot might not be able to react with sufficient speed to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Laboratory of Mobility and the project’s senior engineer.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deviate upwards or downwards, but it cannot move overhead; it can only move on two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to rotate its wheels and not in the infinite directions and in infinite ways as bees do.
For this reason, in addition to acceleration and deceleration functions, Nissan has used the rotation function to help the small robot avoid collisions.
This device only takes a couple of seconds to process the information and act on it.
It does not require either the information or the intuitive logic of the maneuvers performed, so it can work continuously with only a couple of dozens of KB of storage space.
This sounds surprising, but it’s not about the GBs and not even the MBs of the storage space.
This is the first step in the development of technologies for the immediate prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan is predicting to introduce to serial boats over the next ten years.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than a variety of lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system by satellite to guide you to your destination while driving, while avoiding obstacles along the way.
