Morgan Stanley provides its capital to MUFG
Morgan Stanley announced the entry of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG) into its company, which would be the first bank in Japan to spend $9 billion and thus take over 21% of its capital, an innovation due to a sharp fall in its stock market price.
A week after a preliminary settlement was made public, the two banks declared that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley’s common shares at a uniform price of $25.25, resulting in a total of $3 billion.
The accepted price is less than 19% of the price of the share as of August 31st.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the acquisition of convertible shares that will secure it a 10% profit and can be sold back at a price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley stated that the global business will be done on the basis of a uniform average price of $29, which is 28% above the current price.
Morgan Stanley's share, however, fell 6.79% to $23.07 at 17.00 GMT.
“This strategic link represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to holding bank status,” said John Mack, CEO of the American Group.
Morgan Stanley adopted this status last week, which is meant to allow him to expand his business to new areas, but under the supervision of the Federal Reserve.
Their connection with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis forces the biggest names on Wall Street to take a much more cautious stance than before.
The modalities unveiled on Monday also show that the agreement has changed over the past few days: Last Monday Morgan had simply stated that she would sell up to 20% of her shares to Japan for about $8.5 billion.
“A week ago,” said Toshihide Mizuno, Managing Director of MUFG, in Tokyo, “we thought that the stake would consist entirely of ordinary shares.
But given the current economic and market situation, we wanted to reduce the risks and secure ourselves.”
Based on a balanced average price, MUFG will pay 7% below their price for its Morgan Stanley shares.
And the business will go on with a reduction in profit by about 20% per share.
The agreement provides that in one year, MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred shares into common shares if the latter is exchanged within a given period to more than 50% above the sale value, that is to say to about $47.
Morgan Stanley assured that the funds provided by MUFG will enable him to take advantage of investment opportunities, strengthen his balance sheet and increase his sales.
However, a spokesman for the group refused to provide more detailed information on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley should be able to record a payability rate of about 15%, one of the best in the sector.
Morgan said he had "significantly" lowered his balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been hard for the group to watch as their stock market price dropped by half as the price of insolvency insurance soared.
This price fell on Monday, but remained at a high level, at about 12%.
Goldman Sachs, the only other “survivors” of the major investment banks on Wall Street after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the acquisition of Merrill Lynch, announced last week that it had withdrawn $15 billion, partly from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett’s group.
Rafael Correa this Monday in Quito.
The re-establishment of the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, following the example of his like-minded people and friends, it was the third one who put forth the plan for a new constitution.
Mission accomplished, because according to the public results of 80% of the voters, 64% voted 'yes' in the referendum.
According to these results, 28% voted 'No', 7% of the ballots were invalid and 0.7% were submitted empty.
In order for the draft constitution to be adopted, more than half of all votes cast must be voted.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exits of the polling stations and a census of a non-governmental organization had announced a clear victory for "yes" and prophesied to him 63% to 70%.
By the way, on the night of Sunday to Monday, Rafael Correa had demanded the victory of his constitutional draft.
The “constitution has triumphed in an overwhelming way,” he had insured in Guayaquil, the seat of the government 280 kilometers southwest of Quito, and congratulated the Ecuadorians.
Of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales, but also by his Chilean like-minded Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which was held in silence under the Organization of American States (OAS) Observation Board, referred to a text consisting of 444 points to safeguard the <0x60>new socialism', which the President advocates.
The constitutional project transfers state power to the economy by giving it the sole right to ‘development planning’ in a country that largely lives on oil production by foreign companies and the foreign exchange that sends emigrants into the country.
The project, driven by the Correa elected in 2006, also grants the head of state more comprehensive power, which will be able to exercise up to two consecutive mandates of four years each, and will have the opportunity to dissolve the National Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also safeguards the principle of free medical care and education, which the President has already begun to introduce in this country with 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population live below the poverty line.
Ultimately, it also envisages banning the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington to use an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad.
An Egyptian command launched the attack on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions who had been captured ten days ago.
They are in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions, who were held captive in the desert for eleven days, were returned to the Egyptian capital in a healthy and intact manner this Monday afternoon.
In the morning they had been liberated by an Egyptian command in Chad.
Apparently in good condition, the hostages reached al-Maza military base right next to Cairo’s international airport at around 3.30pm aboard a special aircraft.
They were taken directly, without being able to speak to the press, aboard a helicopter to the hospital of Maadi, a foreign district of Cairo, for investigation there.
They all enjoyed “best health” and the kidnappers “were not paid a ransom,” Egyptian tourism minister Zoheir Garanna said on the field.
After being captured on September 19 during an off-road vehicle safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border area of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, the group of hostages was repeatedly taken from one hideout to the next by 35 unknown hijackers.
There are eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and also eight Egyptians: two leaders, four chauffeurs, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptus, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the Special Forces, on board two helicopters, launched the attack at night, just before dawn.
"Shots fell on both sides and half of the hijackers were killed, the rest fled," said the official, who wants to remain anonymous.
He explained that a total of 150 Egyptian special forces had been dispatched to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of the Italian diplomat Franco Frattini reported from Belgrade, where he is now, about the role, the secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces have played.
“We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and performance of our men from the intelligence and special forces,” he explained without further details.
He also denied that a ransom had been paid.
The day before, the Sudanese army had claimed to have stopped an off-road vehicle in a patrol, in which the hijackers were located, of which they killed six, including the leader from Chad, and arrested two.
The army stated that they were connected to a rebel group from Darfur, the Libération du Sudan-Unité (SLA-U) movement, but immediately denied that movement.
Letters - The Silent Majority of Culture
A debate on the financing of culture makes headlines and is a central theme of the current election campaign.
All the better.
But one area of our cultural life continues to be forgotten.
Who will stand up and denounce the miserable sums granted to the small museums, the archives, the archaeological excavations or the national historical sites that are sadly starving?
Which politician will dare to remind the federal government that it is neglecting its monuments and its culturally important structures?
That in Quebec, like in Canada, there are no proper laws that effectively protect our cultural heritage?
Did you know that the French government is providing €3.5 million solely for the restoration of the Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau de Chinon in the Loire Valley?
With our American neighbors, the constitution of their country states that the protection of cultural heritage is part of the American culture, and that this cultural heritage must be protected by all citizens, all members of parliament and all districts of government, in mutual agreement.
In Quebec, the Association of Historical Societies of Quebec, at least 40,000 volunteers, gathered in 211 historical societies, are striving to deal intensively with history, to save a few pennies of the numerous private archives, and to preserve the archaeological remains.
They are also often the watchdogs of our cultural heritage, protesting with the power of despair when promoters and decision makers release their bulldozers on our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When will there be a stage for history and cultural heritage?
Benelux governments nationalize parts of Fortis Bank
With a partial nationalization, the Benelux states want to arm the Belgian-Dutch Fortis Bank, which has become turbulent due to the US financial crisis: the three states provide a total of EUR 11.2 billion to the banking and insurance institution, which also has branches in Hungary, by the way.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held high-level discussions this weekend, together with the President of the European Central Bank and the Commission Competition Authority representative.
In the eurozone, Fortis is the first victim of the international financial market crisis that has lasted for a year, so decisions that are now being made in connection with the bank could have a precedent.
In accordance with the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states buy the respective shares of the bank for about 49 percent.
The bank is likely to sell part of its stakes, especially the insurance activities acquired by Dutch ABN Amro last year.
The shares of Fortis began a steep descent last week, with serious crisis scenarios already emerging in the second half of the week.
However, analysts agree that the bank with its 85,000 employees is far too big for a bankruptcy.
The institute’s securities fell 12% to a 14-year low on Friday.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Given the current share prices, the Group’s market value is EUR 14 billion, but this is unrealistic according to the management.
According to the management, the $700 billion U.S. bailout package and the resulting market uncertainty is to blame for the downturn of Fortis shares.
On Monday, however, the courses rose slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed the Bank’s new Managing Director.
The financial institution was also looking for a private buyer, but it did not find an interested party with a factual offer.
The Belgian government, however, was trying to calm down - no investor should tremble for his money, it said.
So far, there has been no panic among the customers, and the bank’s branches have not been stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent branches, but it also names its own leasing companies.
Fox in the chicken coop
Because of a person’s drug use, in America, life and health insurance often refuse to make a contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear that the data market could become uncontrollable.
"There are privacy programs that match the use of drug data in any case to the consent of the affected person.
These should be in independent hands, otherwise we entrust the fox to the chickens," said Richard Dick, developer of the prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies determine the fees and payout amounts in the event of damage depending on the health condition of the customer, and if the risk is overestimated, the insurance will not be concluded at all.
Previously, the customer was sent to a medical examination and the contract was only concluded with the knowledge of the results of the investigation.
Ten years ago Dick invented a much more favorable method: Using the customer’s identification number, he obtains the data of the last one and a half years from the pharmacies, that is, which preparations were purchased, and the program calculates from which disease the customer suffers and how his health condition is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it can be concluded that his blood fat levels are untreatable, which would automatically rank him in a higher risk group.
There are several versions of the program in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier, so that the insurance companies only have to do the paperwork anymore, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the drawbacks is that many medications can be taken for various purposes, such as for migraines and hot flashes, but also for depression.
The latter is, from the insurers’ point of view, a high-risk factor, while those mentioned before are not.
For the query and processing of the data, their own companies have formed, which, before obtaining the data, ask the patient for his consent.
In the meantime, they have to do so by law, although omissions have not yet been punished.
Some companies even process the results of laboratory tests and link them to the data on drug use to provide an even more accurate picture of patients’ health.
More and more companies have access to the data, and at the same time controlling its use becomes more difficult.
Although there is a separate data protection law for health data, its effect extends only to service providers in the health sector and insurance.
The bill has already been submitted to Congress, under which the authorities could also control the data processing companies.
Dick Richard realizes that this is too little, so he wants to further develop his program so that the data can only be shared with the consent of the affected person.
Another question is, of course, that the person concerned can hardly prevent access to his or her data, as otherwise the insurance companies do not conclude a contract with him or her.
And so the chickens are somehow left to the grace of the fox.
Global menu from Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling trade
As the European Union and India are each other’s leading trading partners, this was the main theme of the Ninth Summit, along with other global issues.
The French-Indian summit is also taking place today, where cooperation in the nuclear energy sector is mainly discussed.
While the European Union recognizes that India is an emerging, democratic great power that should be given more voice and voice in international concerns, the Member States have so far not been able to agree on whether or not to support New Delhi's permanent membership in the UN Security Council.
This question was not discussed at yesterday's ninth summit in Marseille yesterday.
The French President and current EU Council President Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Chief Diplomat Javier Solana received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh. An agreement was reached to double trade over the next five years, i.e. to increase to more than 100 billion euros.
In view of the fact that trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this objective is not even so ambitious.
In this sense, the 26 existing civil aviation agreements with India have also been legally merged into an agreement, so that aviation will also be boosted in the future.
India wants to sign the free trade agreement with the EU by 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the pact.
The aim is to strike a balance in the currently unbalanced relationship between the EU and India: while the Union is India’s number one partner, New Delhi is only ranked nineth among EU partners.
The summit was dedicated to global concerns.
This included the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and terrorism, which both sides strongly condemned, and urged the convening of a UN conference.
The Doha Round should also be completed, with both sides to blame for the failure.
The EU stressed that it is sticking to its energy and climate programme, which means that pollutant emissions are to be reduced by at least 20% by 2020.
India agreed to this, as well as the proposal to conclude a kind of global compromise at the upcoming climate summit and reduce greenhouse gas production by 50 percent by 2050.
The rise in food prices should also be tackled, which is why both support the convening of an international conference on the subject of the financial crisis.
The Indian Prime Minister is visiting the French capital today, where he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, however, contracts to French companies worth EUR 20 billion for the construction of nuclear reactors in India are expected.
According to agency reports, the agreement is to be adopted for 15 years.
More than 300 Italian publishers in Frankfurt
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the International Frankfurt Book Fair.
More than 300 Italian publishers will be present at the 60th Book Fair, the most important international event for the acquisition of rights.
The Frankfurt International Book Fair will be attended by more than 7,000 exhibitors from 101 countries. They will be distributed over the 171,790 square meters of the fair and present over 403,000 titles. Turkey will be the guest of honor of the event.
The Under-Secretary for the Ministry of Cultural Property and Activities Maria Giro will represent the Italian Government during the opening ceremony in the exhibition hall: Italy will be represented in the 264 sqm exhibition hall "Punto Italia".
This will be followed by a press conference near the Room Structure in the exhibition hall 5.0 of the book fair: on this occasion, numbers, trends and perspectives around the publishing industry in Italy will be discussed.
According to the data, the importance of books by foreign writers is decreasing throughout, but especially in the adult and youth sectors.
Billionaire Steve Fossett's small plane found missing a year ago
The small plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire disappeared on a flight over the Nevada Desert on September 3, 2007, was found.
The items have been found on a 3000 m high plateau, in the Sierra Nevada Mammoth Lakes area between the states of California and Nevada.
However, no human remains were found inside the aircraft.
The Sheriff of Madera County, John Anderson, completely blurred the last doubts during a press conference: "The plane was located, where a force was sent, and now we are certain that it was the plane that Steve Fossett flew with on the day of his disappearance."
Mr. Anderson also confirmed that no human remains were found on or near the plane.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The U.S. Office of Traffic Safety (NTSB) noted that just hours after sighting the aircraft, a crew was sent to identify the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which was lost on September 3, 2007, after Fossett took off on a 3-hour flight in Yerington, Nevada.
Yesterday, some of Fossett’s personal belongings were found in California, near the border with Nevada, from a couple near their home at Mammoth Lakes.
These are two ID cards named Fossetts, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a jacket.
The search for Fossett had been abandoned a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned himself a place in history through a long series of records.
In 2002, in his sixth run, he became the first person to orbit the world balloon in a hot air balloon: a two-week, lonely flight.
Three years later, he flew around the world in a single non-stop flight with an airplane.
Among his several records is also a 15445 m high flight over the Andes, this one with a co-pilot.
Glk, the advertising you don't expect
A suv that, thanks to its original design and the special lines, the expansive surface and its clear angles, falls out of the traditional schemes.
Mercedes-Benz has tried to breathe new breath into the sector with this off-roader.
Due to its exceptional characteristics, the presentation of the Suv Glk will also be unconventional, which will be on display in the Mercedes-Benz showroom from 17 October.
The advertising drum, which will accompany the release of the new model, will also appear in a new dress, namely in the form of a 3D campaign – this is a novelty in the automotive sector in the backward Italy.
A project with a maximum effort to be carried out in various phases that will occupy the central shopping mile of Milan, the Corso Como, until November 15.
The first phase will consist of the presentation of the car in shape, with 3D glasses distributed near the Corso Como to give the whole a special look: the new Suv will thus appear in its almost real dimensions as a three-dimensional model.
In fact, the car will appear so apparently from the poster on which it is pictured.
With the help of Elumina8 technology, the new Glk is illuminated at different moments in all its details to reassemble as a whole.
Undoubtedly, it is Mercedes’ concern with this advertising to introduce a new kind of automobile advertising into this rather stereotyped field.
But will this succeed in attracting the interest of future buyers? We will see.
